<subSubSection id="0581CA177A5394B4DA201B3EAA96A3AF" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" type="morphological remarks">
<paragraph id="26809C52B10F115617B70A788506039D" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Morphological remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A614FFD81B353DD9E71B74C9AC3F69F2" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Based on newly examined material, morphological characteristic of 
<taxonomicName id="5B02281DA269C1BC5D053CF122A29497" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Jacobyana</taxonomicName>
is revised and updated with respect to the original description (
<bibRefCitation id="A158F1D1DC28CEAE9682521B29513871" author="Maulik, S" journalOrPublisher="Today &amp; Tomorrow's Printers &amp; Publishers, New Dehli" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" title="The fauna of the British India including Ceylon and Burma. Coleoptera. Chrysomelidae &amp; Halticinae" year="1926">Maulik 1926</bibRefCitation>
). Body roundish, strongly convex (Figs 2, 8, 14). Head with evident setiferous punctures (Figs 3, 9, 15); antenna short, generally not reaching pronotal base (Figs 2, 8, 14); third antennomere clearly thinner than first two antennomeres and about as long or longer than fourth and fifth together (as in 
<taxonomicName id="936727E393439E20F65041CE79A87084" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana piceicollis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piceicollis">Jacobyana piceicollis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="BCB7559EF69DB92FA6A7656F16746DDF" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana flurinae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flurinae">Jacobyana flurinae</taxonomicName>
); distal antennomeres (7 through11) distinctly longer than middle ones (3 through 6). Pronotum (Figs 4, 10, 16) clearly transverse (WP/LP&gt; 2.2), anteriorly narrower than posteriorly, without antebasal furrow; lateral margins distinctly bordered, with anterior setiferous pore rearward towards middle of pronotal side; posterior margin not bordered, clearly sinuous. Elytral punctation (Fig. 17) arranged in regular rows; interstriae flat. Hind femur strongly enlarged; all femora ventrally with a large and generally deep furrow as long as femoral length, with smooth surface, to receive tibiae in resting position; hind tibia dorsally clearly channeled with distinct apical spur; tarsal claw sub-appendiculate (Fig. 7). Ventral surface (Figs 5, 11, 18) with numerous setiferous punctures, generally rather uniformly distributed; procoxal cavities posteriorly open; metasternum about as long as first abdominal sternite; elytral epipleura wide and slightly concave.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ABEB92D4220D47DB6475B85A09CF4564" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Metafemoral spring (Fig. 19) similar to springs of 
<taxonomicName id="0899F721F686E499D919A38CA4C0F85E" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Psylliodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Psylliodes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Psylliodes</taxonomicName>
morpho-group (Furth &amp; Suzuki 1998) but likely constitutes a new morpho-group with dorsal lobe regularly curved, with rather long extended arm; basal edge straight, angled &lt;90° with central axis of dorsal lobe; dorsal edge of ventral lobe straight; basal angle of ventral lobe acute, short, apically pointed; recurve flange distinctly sclerotized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="121BA1407661B13207824BE7158214F1" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="AC4A7F781AE5A9FE91D12FFF69858B56" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F3C4614D807746DDC642289502694F6" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Oriental (India, Nepal, Vietnam and Sri Lanka) (
<bibRefCitation id="EEE640FBC35125E5535AEE523313CA4E" author="Medvedev, LN" journalOrPublisher="Russian Academy of Sciences. KMK Scientific Press Ltd., Moscow" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" title="Alticinae of Indochina" year="2009">Medvedev 2009</bibRefCitation>
) and Afrotropical (Democratic Republic of Congo, Malawi, and Republic of South Africa) Regions (Fig. 1).
</paragraph>
<caption id="6FBCED529308BFF5578D30D1796AC4AE" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<paragraph id="FD4388376A825EDF97FA384B0A87E8CA" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Figure 1. Geographical distribution of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="7794FF8DA8AF576DDCA3F288658A371C" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Jacobyana</taxonomicName>
Maulik.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="ECD9F1E2ADDBC12487DF3921E2903F20" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" type="notes">
<paragraph id="93B8AA60CD9929C853250863F29F9261" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7BB145DBE1F36F2D0C456DBB73425458" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName id="587C6DEB34BDFC6758193AC56AE4C41F" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana bezdeki" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bezdeki">Jacobyana bezdeki</taxonomicName>
sp.n. (LB = 2.64 mm), 
<taxonomicName id="0D4A5722B423E74ABFA5C9E5C2D5DCFF" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana centrafricana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="centrafricana">Jacobyana centrafricana</taxonomicName>
sp. n. (LB = 2.66 mm), and 
<taxonomicName id="DD05EF4DA773AB358CB26175D4056AC8" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana sudafricana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudafricana">Jacobyana sudafricana</taxonomicName>
sp.n. (LB ♂ = 2.25 mm and ♀&gt; 2.43 mm) are the smallest species of the genus (
<bibRefCitation id="648368D1590B7E423AD8028DDB782F06" author="Sprecher-Uebersax, E" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" pagination="191 - 196" title="Zwei neue Alticinenarten der Gattung Jacobyana aus Indien (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae, Alticinae)." volume="75" year="2002">Sprecher-Uebersax 2002</bibRefCitation>
). All new Afrotropical species share a ratio of the length between antennomeres 3 and 4 (= 2) with 
<taxonomicName id="C3AA90196A867DBB81FEB057AB65F402" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
Medvedev from Sri Lanka (known only by a single female). However, all three African species are distinguishable from 
<taxonomicName id="9A899818C81C2EEA3F4B7CFC2E15AA9C" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
by their smaller size (
<taxonomicName id="BF664AD97034113DC18EE9278F6AEFFA" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
: LB = 3.40 mm), interantennal space distinctly narrower than length of first antennomere (as broad as first antennomere in 
<taxonomicName id="D2BECB3484273EBC3E1D631322219805" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
) and, with the exception of some specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="163D5480574057D67320F23555C619C1" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana sudafricana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudafricana">Jacobyana sudafricana</taxonomicName>
sp. n., by the colour of the dorsal integuments, never uniformly black (entirely black in 
<taxonomicName id="2BA5A56C70E43779BC545C7D525EFA75" authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
